06925nam a22007575i 9780822387114DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223871147 a10.1515/97808223871142doi  a(DE-B1597)554259  a(OCoLC)1153776951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aKF4550b.C568 2005eb 7aPOL0060002bisacsh04a342.730222200aCongress and the Constitution /cNeal Devins, Keith Whittington, Mark A. Graber. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (331 p.) :b12 tables, 3 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConstitutional conflicts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tProlegomena for a Sampler: Extrajudicial Interpretation of the Constitution, 1789-1861 -- tCongressional Attitudes toward Constitutional Interpretation -- tConstitutional Analysis by Congressional Staff Agencies -- tHearing about the Constitution in Congressional Committees -- tThe Federal Appointments Process as Constitutional Interpretation -- tLawyers in Congress -- tCongressional Responses to Judicial Review -- tCourt, Congress, and Civil Rights -- tQuasi-Constitutional Law: The Rise of Super-Statutes -- tCongressional Fact Finding and the Scope of Judicial Review -- tInstitutional Design of a Thayerian Congress -- tEvaluating Congressional Constitutional Interpretation: Some Criteria and Two Informal Case Studies -- tCan Congress Be Trusted with the Constitution? The Effects of Incentives and Procedures -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than a decade, the U.S. Supreme Court has turned a skeptical eye toward Congress. Distrustful of Congress's capacity to respect constitutional boundaries, the Court has recently overturned federal legislation at a historically unprecedented rate. This intensified judicial scrutiny highlights the need for increased attention to how Congress approaches constitutional issues. In this important collection, leading scholars in law and political science examine the role of Congress in constitutional interpretation, demonstrating how to better integrate the legislative branch into understandings of constitutional practice.Several contributors offer wide-ranging accounts of the workings of Congress. They look at lawmakers' attitudes toward Congress's role as a constitutional interpreter, the offices within Congress that help lawmakers learn about constitutional issues, Congress's willingness to use its confirmation power to shape constitutional decisions by both the executive and the courts, and the frequency with which congressional committees take constitutional questions into account. Other contributors address congressional deliberation, paying particular attention to whether Congress's constitutional interpretations are sound. Still others examine how Congress and the courts should respond to one another's decisions, suggesting how the courts should evaluate Congress's work and considering how lawmakers respond to Court decisions that strike down federal legislation. While some essayists are inclined to evaluate Congress's constitutional interpretation positively, others argue that it could be improved and suggest institutional and procedural reforms toward that end. Whatever their conclusions, all of the essays underscore the pervasive and crucial role that Congress plays in shaping the meaning of the Constitution.Contributors. David P. Currie, Neal Devins, William N. Eskridge Jr.. John Ferejohn, Louis Fisher, Elizabeth Garrett, Michael J. Gerhardt, Michael J. Klarman, Bruce G. Peabody, J. Mitchell Pickerill, Barbara Sinclair, Mark Tushnet, Adrian Vermeule, Keith E. Whittington, John C. Yoo  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF tit